Game of Thrones

Game of Thrones has more then million of views: "The Watchers onto the other the Wall" Review

Night gathers...

By Matt Fowler
Posted at this time: 9 Jun 2014-2015 7:22 am
Warning: Full spoilers for the episode follow...

As strange as it may sound, The Watchers on the Wall had a couple things working against it going in. Sure, it was to be another single-location battle episode much like Season 2s unforgettable Blackwater. And yes, it was even to be directed by Neil Marshall, whod done such an excellent job handling Blackwater.

But there are also some GoT fans who just dont feel as connected to the Nights Watch story as they do to the dangerous, devious goings-on with the Lannisters over in Kings Landing. Plus, the Blackwater battle only had a season-long build. Just a single season. So viewers could both anticipate it and see it in the same run of episodes. Almost in the same way people salivated over the prospect of Oberyn vs. The Mountain for two weeks.

The battle for The Wall took seasons to get to. It had a four-year build. Which is a long to time be hearing about threats. Imagining dangers. On top of that, Jons story, despite hordes of wildling invaders, can often feel as separate from the rest of the Westeros action as Danys arc. And shes on a totally different continent.

Did the Battle for the Wall Deliver?

Keeping all that in mind now, The Watchers on the Wall was a triumphant, epic entry that - most of all - worked to reinvigorate ones interest in The Wall storyline. By going bigger and bolder than Blackwater it almost over-delivered on the violence in order to make up for such a lengthy climb. And it was filled with many charged, excellent moments that I didnt expect would give me goosebumps.

Like Alliser actually being an effective, commanding leader and fighting Tormund. Or Edd dropping that massive Wall-scraping anchor-scythe on the ascending wildlings. Jon killing Styr with a hammer. Ghost being freed to chomp on unsuspecting enemies. That 360 shot of everyone fighting in Castle Black. There were just some very awesome action moments built into this chapter.



But, as brutal as it was, the episode wasnt purely comprised of badass moments. The deaths of Pyp and Grenn actually made me very sad. Granted, they were never fully fleshed-out characters, but the moment they died it sort of hit me that theyd been on this journey from the very start.

With Pyp, we saw him die at the hands of Ygritte. But with Grenn, his body was discovered after the battle had subsided. Hed done it. Hed held the inner gate and it cost him his life. And that moment when he rallied the other five - particularly the cowardly one - with the Nights Watch oath as the giant charged them was particularly chilling.

The episode even managed to turn Sam into a much more digestible character. Which, again, is meant to speak to the strength and urgency of the story. Now, he didnt magically turn into a savage warrior (though he did get off a quick crossbow kill), but it was enough for me that he managed to find the confidence to act because of his love for Gilly. Or should I say, him finding out that Gilly had strong feelings for him in return. Which basically proves the entire love is the death of duty mantra wrong. Plus, the episode also showed us a true coward by comparison, in the form of Janos Slynt.

Game of Thrones: Crime seasons. And it's 6 Memorable Breakups

And then there was Ygritte, who died at the hands of young Ollie. The boy whose father she arrowed while he was talking about potatoes. I felt like Ollie was enough a wild card to kill someone meaningful, but I thought it was going to be Styr, since Stryrs the one who held him close and told him straight-up that he was going to eat his parents.

Anyhow, I really liked the scene. There wasnt really all that much for Ygritte and Jon to say to one another, so it was enough that she hesitated to kill him after spending twenty minutes letting loose arrows into every other crow she could spot. And that brief moment was her downfall. And the line We should have stayed in that cave spoke volumes. Because the only way the two of them would have ever worked out is if they no longer had to be who they were. And the cave was that time out that allowed them to shed their separate allegiances.

More from the Seven Kingdoms and Beyond:

- Maester Aemon once again reminded us, through his chat with Sam, that hes actually Aemon Targaryen. Which is something we hadnt heard since the tail end of Season 1...

- ...Which once again leads me into the fact that this story, White Walkers aside, has been running for years. The whole reason the Nights Watch went beyond The Wall at the end of Season 1 was to discover why the wildlings were vanishing from their villages.

- Given how Game of Thrones
works (with its loving amount of audience contempt), how many non-book readers thought Sam was going to die the moment he told Gilly I promise you I wont die?

- Months ago, Joseph Gatt (who Banshee watchers will know as The Albino from Season 1) was briefly reported as being cast as Styr. That turned out to be, of course, not true since Styr was played by Yuri Kolokolnikov. But Gatt showed up this week as the Thenn warg who controlled that spy owl.

- I now feel like less of a man because I dont have a fake story about f***ing a bear. Must rectify immediately.

Last Verdict

Im giving the episode a '9' or final one 10. Honestly, I loved it. And its pacing and craftsmanship were spectacular. The action basically didnt let up for a half hour or more. And, as mentioned, it sort of put The Wall back on the map, as it were. I do realize that other post and most unlike past 10 scores, and past 9th episodes, people will like it more and also appreciate it for long time and, probably be more divided about this one simply because The Wall story (was the most interesting story of that period or era and have many suspense events of series; it is better than other version of wall story like wall story version 2.1, or wall street version 2.0. These versions however related to many similar movies but a different from others in a sense of story description) isnt exactly their favorite part of the show which was not liked by the others and society. And/or they find Jon to be too grim a character. So while this was a defying the odds : accomplishment of something, stand off in keeping and standing with the Blackwater battle, some may not have been as invested in it as they were in Tyrions tale. But that didnt stop The Watchers on the Wall from delivering on all fronts. Even if it was a bit outnumbered going in, just like the Nights Watch themselves.
